FEMALE REPRESENTATION IN POLITICS¶

WE WILL BE CHECKING THE FEMALE PARTICIPATION IN LOK SABHA ELECTIONS.¶

Group 18 - Politics¶

Group Members: Purav Patel, Pavithra Kothacheruvu Ravi, Sanyuja Kadam¶

Objective of the Proposed Research¶

In this project we are studying about the participation of women candidates in the Indian general elections. We are looking into how females are represented in the elections and what are the factors that affect the chosen candidates. We will also be identifying probable female candidates winning in a state and the party associated with her. We will be looking into various datapoints in the dataset which will help us determine the chances of winning for a female candidate and various aspects related to the candidate.

Our stakeholder for this research is a political party looking to add strong and influential female candidates for the upcoming elections to their party. This research will provide them with key insights on the participating candidates and will ease their recruitment process to maximize their chances of being elected.

The data used in this research consists of Candidate name, Current party name, Criminal records associated with that candidate, Age, Total assets, Constituency, Age, Previous winning record and finally Gender.

Data Exploration¶

The data set is taken from https://www.kaggle.com/code/themlphdstudent/2004-lok-sabha-election-eda-and-winner-prediction/data?select=LokSabha2019.csv

3.1)Renaming Columns

Lets rename some columns of our datasets. We are renaming 2 columns so that our datasets, Candidate to Candidate Name and Education to Highest Qualiication

In [ ]:
data2004 <- data2004 %>% rename(Candidate.Name = Candidate)
data2009 <- data2009 %>% rename(Candidate.Name = Candidate)
data2014 <- data2014 %>% rename(Candidate.Name = Candidate)
data2019 <- data2019 %>% rename(Candidate.Name = Candidate)
In [ ]:
data2004 <- data2004 %>% rename(Highest.Qualification = Education)
data2009 <- data2009 %>% rename(Highest.Qualification = Education)
data2014 <- data2014 %>% rename(Highest.Qualification = Education)
data2019 <- data2019 %>% rename(Highest.Qualification = Education)

Technically the minimum value for Age for any candidate cannot be 0 also for our analysis we are not considering candidates whose age is greater than 80. So we are cleaning the Age column by deleting those values of Age where , Age is less that 18 and greater than 80

In [ ]:
data2004 <- data2004[-c(which(data2004$Age > 80 | data2004$Age < 18)), ]
data2009 <- data2009[-c(which(data2009$Age > 80 | data2009$Age < 18)), ]
data2014 <- data2004[-c(which(data2014$Age > 80 | data2014$Age < 18)), ]
data2019 <- data2004[-c(which(data2019$Age > 80 | data2019$Age < 18)), ]

10) Project Report

In this project we are studying about the participation of women candidates in the Indian general elections. We are looking into how females are represented in the elections and what are the factors that affect the chosen candidates.

We can clearly see that the female participation in the general elections is significantly less than the male participation. There is a need to change this dynamic.

More women should be encouraged to participate in the elections.That would raise the overall competetiveness of the election.

Workshops should be conducted to educate women on how to represent themselves in a political scenario.

Women should be introduced about concepts of negligible or no liabilities so that they dont get burdened with debt.

Exposure to political things should be provided to students from a young age. Schools can have a seperate cirriculum about general civics and politics. This can help a lot of students develop an interest in political things from a young age.
